  subhead="A homeowner WhatsApps at 7:45am with four photos — close-ups of a damp patch at the base of her dining room wall showing tide marks at about 800mm, white salt deposits crystallising on the plaster, the skirting board showing signs of rot, and a wider shot showing the wall faces the front garden. Her message: 'Morning — this damp has been getting worse since we moved in six months ago. It was just a small patch but now it is spreading. The skirting is going soft. Is this rising damp? Can you survey and tell us what needs doing?' You are loading the van for a survey in Botley — moisture meter, protimeter pins, borescope, and DPC injection kit all packed. Without AI WhatsApp, her message waits until the evening. She messages two more firms; one responds in fifteen minutes with an explanation of rising damp symptoms and offers a Thursday survey. With it, the AI responds instantly, confirms that ground-level damp with salt deposits and timber decay is consistent with rising damp, asks about the property age and whether adjacent rooms show similar signs, and your lead — with four diagnostic photos — is waiting at coffee break."
